11.25.17  3:00 pm   I was watching a barney kessel interview and he was talking about his guitar playing style, and he said a way to make a melody sound more 'full' is to harmonize the melody using different intervals, like harmonizing 'in thirds' or 'in sixths' or whatever. Does harmonizing a melody in thirds mean you play notes that are a 3rd above the melody part, or play notes where the original melody would be a third above what you're playing..

     it could be either one

     like if the melody note is C in the key of C, you'd play an A below the C or you play an E above the C?

     it would usually be either E or actually G. maybe A, depending on the context

     I know either way could work and sound good in different situations, but I guess I don't really understand the terminology.

     to harmonize a melody in 3rds, in reality you will probably be using a mix of major and minor 3rds, with occasional 4ths. but the only way to know for sure what you want is to listen
